  "prompt": "Why do electrons and protons attract each other?",
  "response": "Electrons and protons attract each other due to their opposite electric charges. In the realm of electromagnetism, like charges repel each other while opposite charges attract. This is described by Coulomb's law, which quantifies the electrostatic force between two charged particles. \n\nElectrons carry a negative charge, while protons carry a positive charge. The attractive force between them arises because electric charges create an electric field, and particles with opposite charges experience a force that draws them together along this field. This attraction is fundamental to the structure of atoms, where electrons orbit the nucleus, which is composed of protons and neutrons, leading to the formation of atoms and, ultimately, matter as we know it.",
